 New hire Restricted Stock Units (RSUs) are awarded based on a formula that converts the grant target value from the offer letter into U.S. dollars using the 9-month average exchange rate at the end of the Hooli fiscal quarter. This dollar amount is then divided by the average closing stock price over 21 consecutive business days up until the last full calendar month. The result is rounded down to determine the number of RSUs granted. In the given example, a new hire starting on May 2, 2022, with a grant target value of €200,000 would get approximately 1,300 RSUs after these calculations. To summarize the Q1 section concerning new hire RSU awards, the process involves converting the grant target value in euros (or another currency) to U.S. dollars using the 9-month average exchange rate at the start of the Hooli fiscal quarter. Then, divide this dollar amount by the average closing stock price during the 21 business days leading up to the final full calendar month. Round down the resulting figure to calculate the total RSUs granted to the new employee. Regarding the Q1 section on new hire RSU awards, the company grants RSUs upon completion of certain steps involving financial conversions and stock price assessments. Specifically, the grant target value in foreign currency (e.g., euros) must be converted to U.S. dollars using the 9-month average exchange rate applicable to the commencement of the Hooli fiscal quarter. Subsequently, this amount is divided by the average stock price across 21 business days concluding in the last full calendar month. The quotient, rounded down to the nearest whole number, determines the quantity of RSUs allocated to the new hire. An illustrative case shows a new hire with a €200,000 grant being entitled to around 1,300

